|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208002901/http://www.austriancharts.at/1979_single.asp |archivedate=2014-12-08 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|17\n|-\n|Italy (Singles Chart)<ref name=\"topcharts\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n|Switzerland (Singles Chart)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://hitparade.ch/year.asp?key=1979 |title=Schweizer Jahreshitparade 1979 |publisher=HitParade.ch}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|type=single|artist=Umberto Tozzi|title=Gloria|nocert=yes|salesamount=367,000|salesref=<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php?debut=922 |title=Les Meilleures Ventes Tout Temps de 45 T. / Singles |publisher=Info Disc |language=French |access-date=August 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402145255/http://www.infodisc.fr/S_ToutTemps.php?debut=922 |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Spain|type=single|artist=Umberto Tozzi|title=Gloria|relyear=1980|award=Gold|salesamount=50,000|certref=<ref name=\"Spanish certifications 1979-1990\">{{Cite book |url=http://www.mediafire.com/view/x263f6daopkswo8 |title=S\u00f3lo \u00c9xitos 1959-2002 A\u00f1o A A\u00f1o: Certificados 1979-1990 |publisher=Iberautor Promociones Culturales |language=Spanish |isbn=8480486392|year=2005 }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Laura Branigan version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Gloria\n| cover      = Gloria Laura Branigan US vinyl 12-inch.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Side-A label of the US 12-inch vinyl release, which was housed in a generic Atlantic sleeve and had no original cover art\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Laura Branigan]]\n| album      = [[Branigan]]\n| released   = {{Unbulleted list|{{Start date|1982|06}} {{small|(US)}}|{{Start date|1982|12}} {{small|(UK)}}}}\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n*[[7-inch single|7\"]]\n*[[12-inch single|12\"]]\n*[[CD single|CD]]\n}}\n| recorded   = {{flatlist|\n*1981\n*[[Los Angeles]]\n}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Synthpop]]\n*[[Italo disco]]\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=50}}\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Umberto Tozzi]]\n*[[Giancarlo Bigazzi]]\n*[[Trevor Veitch]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Jack White (producer)|Jack White]]\n*Greg Mathieson\n}}\n| prev_title = [[All Night with Me]]\n| prev_year  = 1982\n| next_title = [[Solitaire (Laura Branigan song)|Solitaire]]\n| next_year  = 1983\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover art\n | type    = single\n | cover   = Laura Branigan - Gloria.png\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Artwork for UK vinyl releases, zoomed-in from the cover art of the parent album, which was also variously used for most non-US single releases\n}}\n}}\n\n===Background===\n[[Atlantic Records]]' managing director Doug Morris suggested that [[Laura Branigan]] work with producer [[Jack White (producer)|Jack White]], who suggested that she record an English version of Tozzi's hit \"Gloria\". Branigan recalled that on hearing the Tozzi track, \"We gave it the American kick and rewrote the lyrics and off she went.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laurabraniganonline.com/images/lvsuncolumn_030703.pdf |title=Branigan knows value of familiar material |work=Las Vegas Sun |via=Laura Branigan website |date=July 3, 2003}}</ref> Branigan's remake of \"Gloria\" was co-produced by White with Greg Mathieson, who had been the arranger of, and the keyboardist on Tozzi's original song, while also being the primary keyboardist on the ''[[Branigan]]'' album.\n\nBranigan told ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine that she and her producers had at first attempted an English version of Tozzi's \"Gloria\" in the romantic mode of the original, changing the title to \"Mario\", but that this seemed ineffective. Ultimately, Branigan recorded an English re-invention of \"Gloria\" as a character study of, in her words, \"a girl that's running too fast for her own steps\", the cover lyrics of which were written by [[Trevor Veitch]], the contractor for the ''Branigan'' album, to which he also contributed guitar work; while Branigan also did her part in co-writing of the cover song's lyrics.\n\nIn 2003, Branigan characterized \"Gloria\" as \"Certainly my signature song. And I always get the same reaction wherever I go, and whenever I perform it ... I have to end every show with that song, and people just go crazy.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laurabraniganonline.com/images/innewswkly_030820.pdf |title=The Lucky One |work=In Newsweekly |via=Laura Branigan website |date=August 20, 2003}}</ref>\n\nBranigan later released a [[Hi-NRG]] re-recording of the song just a few months before her death. \"Gloria 2004\" was released with several remixes on April 26, 2004.\n\n===Popular success===\n\"Gloria\" attained its highest profile via a re-working featured on the 1982 album ''[[Branigan]]'', the first released album by Branigan. Although another selection, \"[[All Night with Me]]\", was chosen as the album's lead-off single, Branigan also performed the cover song during her promotional TV appearances at the time of the album's release in early 1982,<ref name=\"veitchutozzigloria\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=355Fk8drgZE |title=Video of Laura Branigan's cover of 'Gloria' |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=February 23, 2008}}</ref> and that track was released as a single in the summer, first becoming a [[disco]] favorite, and gradually accruing radio support to debut on the pop charts in July 1982. The single reached number 2 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] on November 27, behind [[Lionel Richie]]'s \"[[Truly (song)|Truly]]\", and remained there in the following two weeks, through December 11\u2014when Richie had been supplanted by [[Toni Basil]]'s \"[[Mickey (song)|Mickey]]\".<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1982-12-11 Hot 100 December 11 1982] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109200140/http://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1982-12-11 |date=November 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n\"Gloria\" earned Branigan a nomination for the [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance Female Grammy Award]] for the year 1982. The song remained in the [[Top 40]] for 22 weeks, and its total Hot 100 residency of 36 weeks established a new record for a single by a solo female act,<ref>{{Cite book |author=Joel Whitburn |year=1991 |title=The Billboard Hot 100 Charts: The Eighties (July 10, 1982 - March 12, 1983) |publisher=Record Research, Inc. |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |isbn=0-89820-079-2|author-link=Joel Whitburn }}</ref> breaking the previous record mark. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'' magazine's Top 100 ranked \"Gloria\" at number 1. Certified platinum for sales of one million in the United States alone, \"Gloria\" was also an international success, most notably in [[Australia]] where it held the number 1 position for seven consecutive weeks, from February 7 to March 21, 1983. \"Gloria\" also took Branigan to the Top-10 charts in [[Canada]] at number 1, the [[United Kingdom]] at number 6, [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] at number 4, [[South Africa]] at number 9, [[New Zealand]] at number 6, and number 36 in [[Italy]].\n\n===Notable inclusions===\nBranigan's cover of \"Gloria\" appeared in the musical drama ''[[Flashdance]]'' in 1983, though it was not included in the film's soundtrack. In a nod to her hit, Branigan's rendition of \"Santa Claus Is Coming to Town\" performed on the ''[[Solid Gold (TV series)|Solid Gold]]'' Christmas special featured the background vocalists singing the name \"Gloria\", evoking both Branigan's signature song and the Latin refrain of the Christmas carol \"[[Angels We Have Heard on High]].\"\n\nBranigan guest starred as the lead singer of an all-female band in the February 20, 1983 episode of ''[[CHiPs]]'' titled \"Fox Trap,\" in which she lip-synced to her version of \"Gloria.\"\n\nBranigan's \"Gloria\" was featured in the 2006 video game ''[[Grand Theft Auto: Vice City Stories]]'' on the in-game pop radio station \"Flash FM\".\n\nThe song appears as a cassette tape in ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain]]'', both prequels set in the early 1980s.\n\nThe song has been used in [[Seth MacFarlane]]'s animated TV series ''[[Family Guy]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', and ''[[The Cleveland Show]]''.\n\nAn excerpt of the song was performed by [[Debbie Reynolds]] on ''[[Will & Grace]]'' in the season 3 episode, \"Lows in the Mid-Eighties\"\n\nThe cover song was also incorporated into the score of ''[[Flashdance the Musical]]'' in a scene where the character named Gloria performs a [[pole dance]] routine; sung by Djalenja Scott and Carryl Thomas in Ruthie Stephens' 2008\u201309 national tour of the musical, and by [[Twinnie-Lee Moore]] and Hannah Levane in the 2010\u201311's play at [[West End theatre]], where Charlotte Harwood assumed the role of Gloria.\n\nAt the end of the trailer for the post-apocalyptic comedy series ''[[The Last Man on Earth (TV series)|The Last Man on Earth]]'', Phil Tandy, who at the time happens to be the last person alive, sings \"Gloria\" on a megaphone as a desperate call for contact with a woman.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BwnQ-SbtJug |title=The Last Man On Earth - Fox - Trailer |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Lea Michele]], [[Naya Rivera]] and [[Adam Lambert]] covered this version in the ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' episode \"[[Trio (Glee)|Trio]]\".\n\nIn the ''[[Scorpion (TV series)|Scorpion]]'' episode \"Sci Hard\", Agent [[Cabe Gallo]]'s lemon car had a cassette tape with this version of the song stuck in the car's player. As a result, the song played whenever Cabe used his car in the episode, with Cabe singing it to himself at one point. At the end of the episode, \"Gloria\" plays during the climatic chase scene which ends with the bad guys' motorcycles crashing into Cabe's car, resulting in the tape ejecting and the song ending.\n\nIn 2017, the first episode of the BBC/Netflix series ''[[White Gold (TV series)|White Gold]]'' began with the song.\n\nAn excerpt of the song appears twice in 2017's ''[[I, Tonya]]''. The song appears in the scenes featuring the man who assaulted [[Nancy Kerrigan]], Shane Stant.\n\nThe Branigan version of the song is featured in an episode of the [[The Assassination of Gianni Versace: American Crime Story|second installment]] of the [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] anthology series ''[[American Crime Story]]''. The song plays on the radio as [[Andrew Cunanan]] sings along to it.\n\nBranigan\u2019s cover of the song is used along with other 1980s hits in the ''[[South Park]]'' episode \"[[Splatty Tomato]]\".\n\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 355px\"\n! style=\"background: #F0E68C; font-size: 65%\"|from \"Julianne Moore Danced the Night Away at the Premiere <br> of ''Gloria Bell''\" by Keaton Bell@Vogue.com (5 March 2019)\n|-\n| style=\"font-size: 75%\"| \"[In what's] easily five of the most joyful minutes ever put to film [Gloria Bell] slowly approach[es] the dance floor as her theme song<span style=\"font-size:50%\">...</span>plays & [then] nearly bursts in a fit of ecstasy dancing to the music.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.vogue.com/article/julianne-moore-gloria-bell-premiere |title = Julianne Moore Danced the Night Away at the Premiere of Gloria Bell}}</ref>\n|}\n\nChilean screenwriter/director [[Sebasti\u00e1n Lelio]] utilized the Umberto Tozzi rendition of \"Gloria\" in the 2013 film ''[[Gloria (2013 film)|Gloria]]'': Lelio's 2019 English-language remake ''[[Gloria Bell]]'' features the title character (played by [[Julianne Moore]]) dancing to Branigan's take on the song in a sequence hailed as an essential highlight of the film:<ref>https://www.dispatch.com/entertainmentlife/20190322/movie-review--gloria-bell-julianne-moore-is-knockout-talent-in-working-class-turn</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/gloria-bell-review-1.28473865 |title = Newsday &#124; Long Island's & NYC's News Source &#124; Newsday}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.sfexaminer.com/entertainment/julianne-moore-dances-in-gloria-bell/ | title=Julianne Moore dances in 'Gloria Bell'| date=2019-03-14}}</ref><ref>https://www.yourobserver.com/article/gloria-bell-film-julianne-moore-review-observer</ref>\n\n==== Use by the St. Louis Blues ====\n\nThe [[National Hockey League|NHL]]'s [[St. Louis Blues]] began using Branigan's cover version of \"Gloria\" as its unofficial victory song when they went on a franchise-record 11-game winning streak during the [[2018\u201319 St. Louis Blues season|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/blues/news/gloria-the-story-behind-the-blues-new-old-postgame-victory-song/c-304750776|title=Gloria! The story behind the Blues new (old) postgame victory song|website=Nhl.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> The origins of \"Gloria\"'s association with the Blues comes from when a few Blues players visited a bar in [[South Philadelphia]] called Jacks NYB to watch the \"[[Double Doink]]\" [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs|NFL Wild Card game]] between the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] and [[Chicago Bears]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nhl.com/blues/news/gloria-the-story-behind-the-blues-new-old-postgame-victory-song/c-304750776|title=Gloria! The story behind the Blues new (old) postgame victory song|last=Pinkert|first=Chris|date=February 12, 2019|access-date=May 20, 2019|publisher=NHL Enterprises, L.P.|language=en-US|website=StLouisBlues.com}}</ref><ref name=\"CBCBlues\">{{cite news|title=How a night in a Philadelphia bar inspired the Blues' infectious 'Play Gloria' celebration|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/st-louis-blues-play-gloria-philadelphia-bar-1.5135912|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|website=CBC.ca|date=May 14, 2019|access-date=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Whyno|first=Stephen|title='Play Gloria!' Blues Celebration Song Has Philly Bar Origins|url=https://hosted.ap.org/bendbulletin/article/4670aafe1f764e4aa841785603286713/play-gloria-blues-celebration-song-has-philly-bar-origins|agency=[[Associated Press]]|website=AP.org|date=May 14, 2019|access-date=May 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515032156/https://hosted.ap.org/bendbulletin/article/4670aafe1f764e4aa841785603286713/play-gloria-blues-celebration-song-has-philly-bar-origins|archive-date=May 15, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|A club member kept yelling, \"Play 'Gloria!'\" and DJ Matt Cella obliged by putting on Branigan's catchy pop hit every commercial break. \"They just went nuts when they heard it, and we loved watching it,\" Blues forward [[Robby Fabbri]] said. \"So we just happened to get a win the next day and made it our win song.\" The next day the Blues went on to defeat the [[2018\u201319 Philadelphia Flyers season|Philadelphia Flyers]] in a 3\u20130 shutout. Jacks members say they have trademarked \"Play Gloria\" and they have sold over 700 shirts bearing the phrase.<ref name=\"CBCBlues\" />}}\n\nAt the time, the Blues had the worst record in the league at 15\u201318\u20134, had fired head coach [[Mike Yeo]], called up rookie [[goaltender]] [[Jordan Binnington]] from the minor leagues to replace struggling starter [[Jake Allen (ice hockey)|Jake Allen]], and seemed bound for a lost season. Following their January 7 victory over the Flyers, which was Binnington's first NHL start, the Blues played \"Gloria\" in the locker room to celebrate their victory, with it then becoming a regular locker room ritual. When their stadium's DJ learned of it, he began playing the song in the stadium to rally the team.<ref name = \"Billboard\" /> From January 2019 the Blues would post a 30-10-5 record in the remaining games to finish at 45-28-9 and qualify for a playoff spot, eventually advancing to the [[2019 Stanley Cup Finals]], the team\u2019s first Stanley Cup Final since [[1970 Stanley Cup Finals|1970]], where they defeated the [[Boston Bruins]] in 7 games to win their first Stanley Cup. The dramatic turnaround in the Blues' fortunes following their adoption of \"Gloria\" led to it being embraced as their new victory anthem. The song is played at [[Enterprise Center]] every time the Blues win a game, leading to \"Play Gloria!\" becoming both a [[meme]] and victory chant for Blues fans. Local radio station [[KYKY|Y98]] played the song for 24 hours following the Blues' [[2019 Stanley Cup Playoffs|Game 7]] double-overtime 2&ndash;1 victory over the [[Dallas Stars]] on May 8 and again two weeks later on May 22 after its Game 6 5&ndash;1 win over the [[San Jose Sharks]] to win the Western Conference Championship and advance to the finals. After the Blues defeated the [[Boston Bruins]] in the Stanley Cup Finals, on June 12, Y98 would play \"Gloria\" again for 24 hours. The bands [[Phish]] and [[Vampire Weekend]], who were both holding concerts in St. Louis on the night of Game 7, performed covers of \"Gloria\" when they learned the Blues had won the Cup.<ref name = \"Billboard\">[https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8515917/vampire-weekend-phish-cover-gloria-video-st-louis-blues Vampire Weekend & Phish Cover Laura Branigan's 'Gloria' to Salute NHL Champs St. Louis Blues]</ref>\n\nBranigan's legacy manager Kathy Golik has embraced the trend, with Branigan's verified Twitter page frequently posting support for the Blues, especially during their 2019 playoff run.<ref>[https://fansided.com/2019/05/21/play-gloria-st-louis-blues-win-song-backstory/ Play Gloria! The St. Louis Blues win song has quite the backstory]</ref> Branigan's official website also got updated with a new splash page which expressed support for the Blues and proclaimed Branigan as the \"Original Play Gloria\". Golik stayed in [[St. Louis]] and attended every game and watch party during the Blues' 2019 Stanley Cup run<ref>[https://twitter.com/laurabranigan/status/1136864468372217857 Laura Branigan on Twitter]</ref> while discussing the trend with media outlets. When fans of the [[Boston Bruins]], the Blues' opponent in the [[2019 Stanley Cup Finals]], started re-purposing the \"Play Gloria\" meme it earned a rebuke from Branigan's Twitter page which went viral.<ref>[https://www.kmov.com/news/play-gloria-is-a-blues-thing-laura-branigan-s-twitter/article_fd8f9e4c-770c-11e9-bfcb-b78c9ec9d5c8.html https://www.kmov.com/news/play-gloria-is-a-blues-thing-laura-branigan-s-twitter/article_fd8f9e4c-770c-11e9-bfcb-b78c9ec9d5c8.html]</ref> Custom-made Blues jerseys with Branigan's name and the number 82 surged in popularity during the 2019 Stanley Cup playoffs, with one being displayed on Branigan's Twitter page, along with other Blues merchandise sent by fans. \"Gloria\" reappeared on the iTunes singles chart thanks to the trend, going to number 3 after the Blues won the Stanley Cup.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.thrillist.com/news/nation/play-gloria-st-louis-blues-victory-song-explained | title=How 'Gloria' Became the St. Louis' Song & Why Every Keeps Saying 'Play Gloria!'| date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/laurabranigan/status/1139200893574877186?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet Laura Branigan on Twitter]</ref> \"Gloria\" would also re-enter the ''Billboard'' charts in the wake of the Blues' championship, landing at #46 on the [[Digital Songs|Billboard Digital Song Sales]] chart for the week of June 22, 2019.<ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/music/laura-branigan/chart-history/digital-song-sales/song/818633 |title = Laura Branigan Gloria Chart History}}</ref> Golik noted that streams of \"Gloria\" have surged across all platforms and this has had a \"trickle down\" effect to the rest of Branigan's catalog, with her other hit songs such as \"[[Self Control (Laura Branigan song)|Self Control]]\", \"[[Solitaire (Laura Branigan song)|Solitare]]\" and \"[[How Am I Supposed to Live Without You]]\" seeing significant upticks in streams and downloads during the 2019 Stanley Cup Playoffs.<ref name = \"Forbes\" /> The song's resurgence in popularity has led to Branigan's management getting numerous requests for live performances and public appearances, leading them to release a statement reminding the public that Branigan is deceased, as well as adding a note about this to her social media accounts.<ref>[https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/ny-my-news-laura-branigan-dead-gloria-stlouis-blues-song-20190221-story.html The 1982 song 'Gloria' is a hit again and singer Laura Brannigan \u2014 who died in 2004 \u2014 keeps being asked to perform it live]</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' described \"Gloria\" as an \"unlikely championship anthem\" and noted that the Blues' Stanley Cup victory could permanently alter the meaning and legacy of the song, with it becoming forever associated with the St. Louis Blues and ice hockey in general.<ref name = \"Forbes\">[https://www.forbes.com/sites/jerrybeach/2019/06/09/one-more-st-louis-blues-win-laura-branigans-gloria-becomes-an-unlikely-championship-anthem/#400c7aba68bf One More St. Louis Blues Win, And Laura Branigan's 'Gloria' Becomes An Unlikely Championship Anthem]</ref> Golik has also stated her belief that Branigan and \"Gloria\" \"will forever be intertwined\" with the Blues and the city of St. Louis.<ref>[https://twitter.com/laurabranigan/status/1141207428949843969?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet Laura Branigan on Twitter]</ref> When asked how she thought Branigan would have reacted to the \"Play Gloria\" meme had she lived to see it, Golik said, \"She was very sincere, very down to Earth, she would just have been very touched by it all. If she were here, I know she would have participated in a very big way. I know she\u2019s there in spirit. To see them win and to hear that song blaring and coming up in the arena and looking around and seeing people singing out as loud as they can, cheering and having a good time, it\u2019s indescribable what that\u2019s like.\u201d<ref name = \"Forbes\" />\n\n===Track listings===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 7\" single<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria/release/1174610 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria (Vinyl, 7\") at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria\n| length1         = 4:50\n| title2          = Living a Lie\n| length2         = 3:41\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 12\" single<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria/release/4699866 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria (Vinyl, 12\") at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria\n| note1           = Extended version\n| length1         = 5:53\n| title2          = Living a Lie\n| length2         = 3:41\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 7\" single {{nobold|(UK)}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria/release/1443642 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria (Vinyl, 7\" UK) at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria\n| length1         = 4:50\n| title2          = I Wish We Could Be Alone\n| length2         = 3:18\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 7\" single {{nobold|(Italy)}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria/release/3198628 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria (Vinyl, 7\" Italy) at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria\n| length1         = 4:50\n| title2          = All Night With Me\n| length2         = 3:52\n}}\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = CD single {{nobold|\u2013 The Remixes}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria-99-The-Remixes/release/4252902 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria '99 (The Remixes) (CD) at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria '99\n| note1           = DJ-C radio edit\n| length1         = 3:30\n| title2          = Gloria '99\n| note2           = DJ-C extended mix\n| length2         = 4:32\n| title3          = Gloria '99\n| note3           = Tinka's house mix\n| length3         = 6:29\n| title4          = Gloria '99\n| note4           = Tinka's dub mix\n| length4         = 6:31\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = CD single {{nobold|\u2013 2004 Mixes}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria-2004/release/309532 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria 2004 (CD) at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria 2004\n| note1           = Prodygee & Davis radio mix\n| length1         = 3:23\n| title2          = Gloria 2004\n| note2           = Alternative radio version\n| length2         = 3:38\n| title3          = Gloria 2004\n| note3           = S.A.D. radio mix\n| length3         = 4:09\n| title4          = Gloria 2004\n| note4           = Prodygee & Davis remix\n| length4         = 6:16\n| title5          = Gloria 2004\n| note5           = S.A.D. club mix\n| length5         = 6:59\n| title6          = Gloria 2004\n| note6           = Prodygee & Davis club mix\n| length6         = 6:01\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 12\" single {{nobold|\u2013 2004 Mixes}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.discogs.com/Laura-Branigan-Gloria-2004/release/357724 |title=Laura Branigan - Gloria 2004 (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=[[Discogs]] |accessdate=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n| title1          = Gloria 2004\n| note1           = Discotronix remix\n| length1         = 7:01\n| title2          = Gloria 2004\n| note2           =